 references to religious visual culture and the responses they incited in cross-confessional negotiations. She reveals some of the anxieties about what it meant to belong to different ethnic or religious communities and how these communities interacted with each other within the fluid boundaries of the Mediterranean world. Focusing on the religious image as a point of contact between individuals of diverse beliefs and practices, The Arts of Encounter presents an original and necessary perspective on how Christian-Muslim relations were perceived and conveyed in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aChristian art and symbolism in literature. 0aChristianity and other religionsxIslam. 0aReligion and culturezSpain. 0aSpanish literatureyClassical period, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aAljamiado.  aChristian-Muslim encounters.  aInquisition.  aMediterranean.  aMoriscos.  aRenaissance.  aart history.  acaptivity.  aearly modern Spain.  agolden age literature.  areligious images.  avirgin Mary.  avisual culture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076715540uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148750931640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487509316423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487509316/original  a978-3-11-076715-5  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK